[{"id":"VR188136","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR188133.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">What happens to the magnitude of the angular momentum of the disk-rod system with respect to the pivot during the time interval between Figure 1 and Figure 2, and why?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR188136_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows 2 figures labeled figure 1 and figure 2 which display 3 different views of the same disk and rod. The first figure 1 view is the perspective view which shows a disk of mass m moving to the right toward the rod at a speed of v sub i. The second figure 1 view is a top view which displays the same set up and shows that the rod has a length of l and the disk has a mass of m. In figure 2, another top view is shown of the same materials but a different set up. The disk is now moving to the left at a speed of v sub f away from the rod, and the rod is now slanted to the right at a degree of theta sub f from the vertical.\" height=\"193\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR188133.g03.png\" width=\"620\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A disk of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\"><math alttext=\"m\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> slides with negligible friction to the right with speed <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub i\"><math alttext=\"v sub i\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> on a horizontal table. The disk collides elastically with a uniform rod of length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"l\"><math alttext=\"l\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mo>ℓ</mo></mstyle></math></span></span> that is at rest and free to pivot about one end, as shown in Figure 1 above. The disk rebounds to the left with speed <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub f\"><math alttext=\"v sub f\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, and the rod rotates with friction and stops at a final angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub f\"><math alttext=\"theta sub f\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from its initial position, as shown in Figure 2.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It decreases because the disk reverses its direction of motion.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It decreases because an external torque is exerted by friction.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It does not change because there was no angular momentum before the collision.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It does not change because angular momentum was conserved during the collision.</p>"],"answer":1}]